countries.Name: Belgium
countries.Draft text 1: Belgium has the highest breast cancer incidence rate in the world, but fewer women are likely to die from the disease because of early detection and effective treatment options.

countries.Name: Italy
countries.Draft text 1: Although it is in Southern Europe, where fewer women tend to get breast cancer, Italy's incidence rate is closer to that found in Western European countries.

countries.Name: South Korea
countries.Draft text 1: While breast cancer is less common in South Korea than in other highly-developed nations, the number of incidences have risen in recent years â€” due in part to a more Western lifestyle that includes greater consumption of fatty food.

countries.Name: Cuba
countries.Draft text 1: Trends in death rates have been stable in Cuba since 1980.

countries.Name: Mexico
countries.Draft text 1: Mortality rates in Mexico have risen since the mid-1980s, in part due to increases in obesity, delays in child bearing age, and use of postmenopausal hormones.
countries.Draft text 2: Breast cancer is the leading cause of cancer death among women in Mexico. Most Mexican women are diagnosed with breast cancer at a late stage. In 2006, less than 20 of Mexican women reported being screened for the disease.

scenes.title: Where Is Breast Cancer?
scenes.text: Breast cancer is the worldâ€™s most common cancer in women, with an estimated 1.4 million new cases diagnosed every year.

scenes.title: Where Does Breast Cancer Kill?
scenes.text: While women in highly developed countries have higher diagnosis rates of breast cancer, women in the developing world who have breast cancer are more likely to die from the disease.
scenes.note: For each country, deaths per 100 cases were calculated by dividing mortality rate by incidence rate.

scenes.title: High Mortality in Africa
scenes.text:
Many of the poorest countries are in Africa, where a high percentage of breast cancer cases result in death.
Poverty and misinformation keep women from seeking medical help. Even those who receive a diagnosis earlier can face delays in treatment because of scarce resources and dysfunctional health systems.
scenes.note: Incomplete reporting can make rates of breast cancer in developing countries look lower than they are.

scenes.title: Divide Among Mid-Level Nations
scenes.text:
Among women in moderately developed countries, incidence is relatively low but mortality is high.
An exception is China, where incidence and mortality have been lower.

scenes.title: Wealthier Nations
scenes.text:
Among more highly developed nations, Arab countries tend to have lower incidence but higher mortality.
By comparison, the ratio of deaths to new cases is lower in Latin America.

scenes.title: The Richest Countries
scenes.text: Incidence is high but mortality is low in the United States and many Western and Northern European countries, in part because of a history of widespread screening and access to treatment.
